  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements designed to combat money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- International standard-setting body for anti-money laundering efforts\n- Provides guidelines for 39 recommended actions for governments\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention against Corruption\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision Guidelines\n- Sets international banking standards for detecting and preventing money laundering\n\n4. The Egmont Group\n- International network of financial intelligence units\n- Facilitates information sharing between countries\n\n5. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establish common standards for member states\n\nMost countries have domestic laws implementing these international standards, requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income and to disrupt financial networks supporting criminal activities.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include significant fines, asset seizure, and criminal prosecution.",
